] for {{ushr|GA|3}}. The district stretches from the southern suburbs of [[Atlanta]] to the northern suburbs of [[Columbus, Georgia|Columbus]].\n\nA [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], he previously served as the [[mayor]] of [[West Point, Georgia]], a city located between [[LaGrange, Georgia|LaGrange]] and Columbus.\n\nFerguson was born in [[Langdale, Alabama]] in 1966<ref>{{cite web |url=http://info.cqrollcall.com/rs/764-XAC-282/images/CQ-NewMemberGuide-115thCongress.pdf |title=Guide to the New Congress |publisher=[[Roll Call]] |accessdate=January 3, 2017}}</ref> and graduated from the [[University of Georgia]], and the [[Medical College of Georgia]].<ref>[http://thecitizen.com/government-politics/citizen-qa-%E2%80%94-west-point-mayor-ferguson-seeks-3rd-district-seat]</ref> He served as an [[alderman]] for West Point, and then as mayor of West Point from 2008 through 2016, when he resigned to focus on his race for the House of Representatives.\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n=== Election ===\nFerguson ran for the third district seat to fill the void left by retiring Republican incumbent [[Lynn Westmoreland]]. In a contentious battle, Ferguson found his way into the Republican primary runoff against State Senator [[Mike Crane]]. On July 26, 2016, Ferguson soundly defeated Crane with 54% of the vote.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://results.enr.clarityelections.com/GA/62848/174629/en/summary.html|title=GA - Election Results|website=results.enr.clarityelections.com|access-date=2018-03-03}}</ref> He defeated [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] nominee Angela Pendley in the November 2016 general election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://politics.blog.ajc.com/2016/07/26/chamber-of-commerce-backed-drew-ferguson-has-the-edge-in-3rd-district-gop-runoff/|title=Chamber of Commerce-backed Drew Ferguson wins 3rd District GOP runoff - Political Insider blog|date=July 26, 2016|work=Atlanta Journal Constitution|accessdate=July 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nRep. Ferguson was sworn into office January 3, 2017.\n\nFerguson voted in favor of the [[American Health Care Act of 2017]] on May 4, 2017.<ref>http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2017/roll256.xml</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on the Budget|Committee on the Budget]]'''\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Education and the Workforce|Committee on Education and the Workforce]]'''\n**[[United States House Education Subcommittee on Workforce Protections|Subcommittee on Workforce Protections]]\n**[[United States House Education Subcommittee on Health, Employment, Labor, and Pensions|Subcommittee on Health, Employment, Labor, and Pensions]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure|Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure]]'''\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Economic Development, Public Buildings and Emergency Management|Subcommittee on Economic Development, Public Buildings and Emergency Management]] (Vice Chair)\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Highways and Transit|Subcommittee on Highways and Transit]]\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment|Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment]]\n* '''[[Republican Study Committee]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|author=|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov/|format=|publisher=|date=|accessdate=November 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\n\n=== Education ===\n\nFerguson opposes the [[Common Core State Standards Initiative]].<ref name=\"OTIEd\">{{cite web|title=Drew Ferguson on Education|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/GA/Drew_Ferguson_Education.htm|website=On The Issues|accessdate=December 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Economic issues===\n\nFerguson opposes federal spending to promote economic growth.<ref name=\"OTIBudget\">{{cite web|title=Drew Ferguson on Budget & Economy|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/GA/Drew_Ferguson_Budget_+_Economy.htm|website=On The Issues|accessdate=December 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nFerguson voted in favor of the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]].<ref name=\"Almukhtara\">{{cite web|last1=Almukhtara|first1=Sarah|title=How Each House Member Voted on the Tax Bill|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/12/19/us/politics/tax-bill-house-live-vote.html?_r=0|website=The New York Times|accessdate=December 25, 2017|date=December 19, 2017}}</ref> He says that middle-class families will get [[tax relief]] and that the bill will enable his middle-class constituents to save more money and that the bill will \"positively impact your life.\" He claims that the bill will simply the [[tax code]] and remove \"existing loopholes\" that \"can only spur economic growth.\"<ref name=\"Zozaya122017\"/> He says that the tax bill \"creates an environment where businesses and innovators can grow, create jobs and increase wages for hard-working employees.\"<ref name=\"Trubey122117\">{{cite web|last1=Trubey|first1=J. Scott|last2=Hallerman|first2=Tamar|title=Georgia businesses hail tax bill, but whether growth comes isn\u2019t clear|url=http://www.myajc.com/news/local/georgia-businesses-hail-tax-bill-but-whether-growth-comes-isn-clear/0VhHkx4sEzTqDqfrV0cPXP/|website=myAJC|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|accessdate=December 25, 2017|language=en}}</ref> He called the passing of the bill a \"absolutely a great, great step for America.\"<ref name=\"Zozaya122017\">{{cite web|last1=Zozaya|first1=Jose|title=GA reps react to latest tax bill's approval in Congress|url=http://www.wtvm.com/story/37111664/ga-reps-react-to-latest-tax-bills-approval-in-congress|website=WTVM|accessdate=December 25, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Abortion ===\n\nFerguson believes that life begins at [[Fertilisation|conception]]. He supports defunding [[Planned Parenthood]] at both local and national government levels.<ref name=\"OTIAbortion\">{{cite web|title=Drew Ferguson on Abortion|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/GA/Drew_Ferguson_Abortion.htm|website=On The Issues|accessdate=December 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Drug policy===\n\nFerguson opposes the legalization of [[marijuana]].<ref name=\"OTIDrugs\">{{cite web|title=Drew Ferguson on Drugs|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/GA/Drew_Ferguson_Drugs.htm|website=On The Issues|accessdate=December 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===LGBT rights===\n\nFerguson opposed the federal government's decision regarding [[bathroom bill]]s. In response to the Obama administration telling public schools to allow transgender people to use whichever bathroom they prefer, Ferguson said \"Common sense has fled the addled brains of our nations leaders. Kickstands to the left, hoo ha's to the right. We don't need the President to make this decision for us.\"<ref name=\"Bluestein51616\">{{cite web|last1=Bluestein|first1=Greg|last2=Tamar|first2=Hellerman|title=The growing bathroom backlash from Georgia Republicans {{!}} Political Insider blog|url=http://politics.blog.ajc.com/2016/05/16/the-growing-bathroom-backlash-from-georgia-republicans/|website=AJC|accessdate=December 25, 2017}}</ref> He also opposes [[same-sex marriage]].<ref name=\"OTICivilRights\">{{cite web|title=Drew Ferguson on Civil Rights|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/GA/Drew_Ferguson_Civil_Rights.htm|website=On The Issues|accessdate=December 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFerguson and his wife, Elizabeth, have four children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lagrangenews.com/news/8416/drew-ferguson-to-resign-as-west-point-mayor|date=February 1, 2016|work=Lagrange News|title=Drew Ferguson to resign as West Point mayor|first=Tyler H.|last=Jones|accessdate=July 28, 2016}}\n</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://ferguson.house.gov/ Congressman Drew Ferguson]\n*[https://fergusonforgeorgia.com/ Campaign website]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Georgia/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Drew_Ferguson_%5BR-3%5D|Drew Ferguson}}\n{{CongLinks | congbio = F000465 | fec = H6GA03113 